04946nam a22007335i 9780691236988DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912369887 a10.1515/97806912369882doi  a(DE-B1597)600741  a(OCoLC)1269268690  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSCI0820002bisacsh04a930.12221 aNur, Amos, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aApocalypse :bEarthquakes, Archaeology, and the Wrath of God /cAmos Nur, Dawn Burgess. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b98 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 King Agamemnon's Capital -- tChapter 2 How Earthquakes Happen -- tChapter 3 History, Myth, and the Reliability of the Written Record -- tChapter 4 Clues to Earthquakes in the Archaeological Record -- tChapter 5 Under the Rubble: Human Casualties of Earthquakes -- tChapter 6 Qumran and the Dead Sea Scrolls: Destruction That Preserves -- tChapter 7 Expanding the Earthquake Record in the Holy Land -- tChapter 8 Earthquake Storms and the Catastrophic End of the Bronze Age -- tChapter 9 Rumblings and Revolutions: Political Effects of Earthquakes -- tChapter 10 Earthquakes and Societal Collapse -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat if Troy was not destroyed in the epic battle immortalized by Homer? What if many legendary cities of the ancient world did not meet their ends through war and conquest as archaeologists and historians believe, but in fact were laid waste by a force of nature so catastrophic that religions and legends describe it as the wrath of god? Apocalypse brings the latest scientific evidence to bear on biblical accounts, mythology, and the archaeological record to explore how ancient and modern earthquakes have shaped history--and, for some civilizations, seemingly heralded the end of the world. Archaeologists are trained to seek human causes behind the ruins they study. Because of this, the subtle clues that indicate earthquake damage are often overlooked or even ignored. Amos Nur bridges the gap that for too long has separated archaeology and seismology. He examines tantalizing evidence of earthquakes at some of the world's most famous archaeological sites in the Mediterranean and elsewhere, including Troy, Jericho, Knossos, Mycenae, Armageddon, Teotihuacán, and Petra. He reveals what the Bible, the Iliad, and other writings can tell us about the seismic calamities that may have rocked the ancient world. He even explores how earthquakes may have helped preserve the Dead Sea Scrolls. As Nur shows, recognizing earthquake damage in the shifted foundations and toppled arches of historic ruins is vital today because the scientific record of world earthquake risks is still incomplete. Apocalypse explains where and why ancient earthquakes struck--and could strike again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchaeology and natural disasters. 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aEarthquakesxEconomic aspects. 0aEarthquakesxHistory. 0aEarthquakesxPolitical aspects. 0aEarthquakesxSocial aspects. 0aExcavations (Archaeology). 0aExtinct cities. 0aHuman beingsxEffect of environment onxHistory. 0aSocial changexHistory. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Seismology & Volcanism.2bisacsh1 aBurgess, Dawn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691236988zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691236988423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691236988/original  